{{Infobox book | name = Mozi | title_orig = {{no italic|墨子}} | translator = | image = Mozi.jpg | image_size = 225px | caption = | author = (trad.) [[Mozi|Mo Di]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = China | language = [[Classical Chinese]] | series = | genre = [[Philosophy]] | publisher = | release_date = | english_release_date = | media_type = | pages = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} {{infobox Chinese |pic=Mozi (Chinese characters).svg |piccap="Mozi" in [[seal script]] (top) and regular (bottom) Chinese characters |picupright=0.45 |c=墨子 |l="[The Writings of] Master Mo" |p=Mòzǐ |w=Mo<sup>4</sup>-tzŭ<sup>3</sup> |gr=Mohtzy |mi={{IPAc-cmn|m|o|4|.|z|^|3}} |j=Mak<sup>6</sup>-zi<sup>2</sup> |ci={{IPAc-yue|m|ak|6|.|z|i|2}} |wuu=Meʔ tzy |y=Mahk-jí |tl=Ba̍k-tzú |mc=Mok-tsí |oc-bs=&#42;C.mˤak tseʔ }}
The '''''Mozi''''' ({{zh|c=墨子}}) is an ancient Chinese text from the [[Warring States period]] (476{{ndash}}221{{sbc}}) that expounds the philosophy of [[Mohism]]. It propounds such Mohist ideas as impartiality, meritocratic governance, economic growth, and aversion to ostentation, and is known for its plain and simple language.
The chapters of the ''Mozi'' can be divided into several categories: a core group of 31 chapters, which contain the basic philosophic ideas of the Mohist school; several chapters on logic, which are among the most important early Chinese texts on logic and are traditionally known as the "Dialectical Chapters"; five sections containing stories and information about Mozi and his followers; and eleven chapters on technology and defensive warfare, on which the Mohists were expert and which are valuable sources of information on ancient Chinese military technology.{{sfnp|Knechtges|2010|p=677}} There are also two other minor sections: an initial group of seven chapters that are clearly of a much later date, and two anti-Confucian chapters, only one of which has survived.
The Mohist philosophical school died out in the 3rd century BC, and copies of the ''Mozi'' were not well preserved. The modern text has been described as "notoriously corrupt" {{ndash}} of its 71 original chapters, 18 have been lost and several others are badly fragmented.{{sfnp|Graham|1993|p=339}}{{sfnp|Nivison|1999|p=762}}
==Authorship== {{main|Mozi}} The ''Mozi'', as well as the entire philosophical school of [[Mohism]], is named for and traditionally ascribed to [[Mo Di]], or "Master Mo" ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: ''Mòzǐ'' 墨子), a figure of the 5th century BC about whom nothing is reliably known.{{sfnp|Nivison|1999|p=760}} Most sources describe him as being from the [[Lu (state)|State of Lu]]—though one says that he was from the [[Song (state)|State of Song]]—and say that he traveled around the various [[Warring States period|Warring States]] trying to persuade their rulers to stop attacking each other.{{sfnp|Knechtges|2010|p=677}} Mozi seems to have come from a humble family,{{sfnp|Knechtges|2010|p=677}} and some elements of the book suggest that he may have been some type of artisan or craftsman, such as a [[carpenter]].{{sfnp|Nivison|1999|p=760}} Some scholars have theorized that the name Mo (墨), which means "ink", may not truly be a surname, but could be indicative of him having undergone the branding or tattooing that was used in ancient China as a form of corporal punishment for criminals.{{sfnp|Nivison|1999|p=760}}{{sfnp|Watson|1999|p=64}}
==Content== The ''Mozi'' originally comprised 71 chapters, but 18 of these have been lost and a number of others are damaged and fragmented. The text can be divided into a total of six sections:{{sfnp|Knechtges|2010|p=677}}{{sfnp|Graham|1993|pp=336–37}}{{sfnp|Nivison|1999|pp=761–63}}
*'''Chapters 1–7''': a group of miscellaneous essays and dialogues that were clearly added at a later date and are somewhat incongruous with the rest of the book. *'''Chapters 8–37''': a large group of chapters{{mdash}}of which seven are missing and three are fragmentary{{mdash}}that form the core ''Mozi'' chapters, and elucidate the ten main philosophical doctrines of the Mohist school of thought. Mozi is frequently referenced and cited in these chapters. *'''Chapters 38–39''': two chapters{{mdash}}of which only chapter 39 survives{{mdash}}entitled "Against Confucianism" (''Fēi Rú'' 非儒), containing polemical arguments against the ideals of [[Confucianism]]. These chapters are sometimes grouped with chapters 8–37. *'''Chapters 40–45''': a group of five chapters, often called the "Dialectical Chapters", which are some of the most unique writings of ancient China, treating topics in [[logic]], [[epistemology]], [[ethics]], [[geometry]], [[optics]], and mechanics. These chapters are dense and difficult, largely because the text is badly garbled and corrupted. *'''Chapters 46–51''': six chapters{{mdash}}of which chapter 51, including even its title, has been lost{{mdash}}that contain stories and dialogues about Mozi and his followers. These chapters are probably of somewhat later date, and are probably partly fictional. *'''Chapters 52–71''': a group of chapters{{mdash}}nine of which have been lost{{mdash}}known as the "Military Chapters", containing instructions on defensive warfare, supposedly from Mozi to his chief disciple Qin Guli. These chapters, like the "Dialectical Chapters", are badly damaged and corrupted.
==Selected translations== The damaged nature of the later chapters of the ''Mozi'' have made its translations highly difficult, and often requires translators to repair and re-edit the text before translating. The first ''Mozi'' translation in a Western language{{mdash}}the 1922 German translation of Alfred Forke{{mdash}}was done before these problems were well understood, and thus contains a large number of errors in the "Dialectical" and "Military" chapters.{{sfnp|Graham|1993|p=340}} Only in the late 20th century did accurate translations of the later ''Mozi'' chapters appear.
*{{de icon}} Alfred Forke (1922), ''Mê Ti: des Socialethikers und seiner Schüler philosophische Werke'', Berlin: Kommissions-verlag des Vereinigung wissenshafticher Verleger. * Y. P. Mei (1929), ''The Ethical and Political Works of Motse'', London: Probsthain. Reprinted (1974), Taipei: Ch'eng-wen. * [[Burton Watson]] (1963), ''Mo Tzu: Basic Writings'', New York: Columbia University Press. * [[Angus Charles Graham|A. C. Graham]] (1978), ''Later Mohist Logic, Ethics, and Science'', Hong Kong: Chinese University Press. * Ian Johnston (2010), ''The Mozi: A Complete Translation'', Hong Kong: Chinese University Press.
Many ''Mozi'' translations into modern [[Mandarin Chinese]] and [[Japanese language|Japanese]] exist.
