{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}
{{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}}
'''Victor Howard ("Vic") Dudman''' (1935–2009) was an Australian [[logician]] based at [[Macquarie University]].

He was greatly influenced by [[Willard Van Orman Quine]] on whose work he based his undergraduate logic courses.

He is particularly noted for his views on the interpretation of the [[material conditional]]. [[David Kellogg Lewis|David Lewis]], a frequent visitor to Australian departments of logic, once noted "If Dudman's view is correct, and I cannot at the moment see what is wrong with it, then almost everything I have written on conditionals is mistaken".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://users.ox.ac.uk/~ball0888/manifesto/if.htm#intro |title=Archived copy |accessdate=11 January 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604164606/http://users.ox.ac.uk/~ball0888/manifesto/if.htm |archivedate=4 June 2011 }}</ref>

[[Jean Curthoys]] saw through the press and wrote an introduction to ''[http://www.palgrave.com/products/title.aspx?pid=581817 Victor Dudman's Grammar and Semantics]'' (Palgrave Macmillan, 2012).

